			<h4><a id="comment_link_64409876" name="comment_link_64409876" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23296940&amp;cid=64409876" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64409876)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64409876" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64409876); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~JBeretta">JBeretta</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~JBeretta">( 7487512 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64409876"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64409876">What paper airplane counteracts Earth gravity?  Birds and bugs convert chemical energy into motion. i.e. it's an internal conversion. They use that energy to counteract the pull of gravity. A paper airplane does no such thing.  A paper airplane generates no energy and is not counteracting anything.  100% of its energy is what you gave it initially or what is imparted on it by the air (updrafts, currents, etc). Without constant additional energy being given to it, the paper-airplane will lose to gravity.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64409876">

</div>
</div>

